03472nmm a2200553Ia 9781501723940DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017239407 a10.7591/97815017239402doi  a(DE-B1597)515497  a(OCoLC)1083587523  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a616.89/00943/090342221 aEngstrom, Eric J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aClinical Psychiatry in Imperial Germany :bA History of Psychiatric Practice /cEric J. Engstrom. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in the History of Psychiatry0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe psychiatric profession in Germany changed radically from the mid-nineteenth century to the beginning of World War I. In a book that demonstrates his extensive archival knowledge and an impressive command of the primary literature, Eric J. Engstrom investigates the history of university psychiatric clinics in Imperial Germany from 1867 to 1914, emphasizing the clinical practices and professional debates surrounding the development of these institutions and their impact on the course of German psychiatry.The rise of university psychiatric clinics reflects, Engstrom tells us, a shift not only in asylum culture, but also in the ways in which social, political, and economic issues deeply influenced the practice of psychiatry. Equally convincing is Engstrom's argument that psychiatrists were responding to and working to shape the rapidly changing perceptions of madness in Imperial Germany. In a series of case studies, the book focuses on a number of important clinical spaces such as the laboratory, the ward, the lecture hall, and the polyclinic. Engstrom argues that within these spaces clinics developed their own disciplinary economies and that their emergence was inseparably intertwined with jurisdictional contests between competing scientific, administrative, didactic, and sociopolitical agendas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aMental illnesszGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aPsychiatryzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 4aEurope. 4aHistory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172394040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501723940423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501723940/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles